        Value Sign # 10: Sharpe Ratio โ The Sharpe ratio is the measure of risk-adjusted return of a financial portfolio. A portfolio with a higher Sharpe ratio is considered superior relative to its peers. A risk-adjusted return is a measure of an investmentโs return or potential earnings that considers the degree of risk that must be incurred to achieve it. Sharpe ratio is a measure of excess portfolio return over the risk-free rate relative to its standard deviation. Normally, the Treasury bill rate is taken as the proxy for the risk-free rate.

      The formula for calculating the Sharpe ratio is {R (p) โ R (f)} /s (p)

     Where R (p): Portfolio return, R (f): Risk-free rate of return, s (p): Standard deviation of the portfolio

Sharpe is used to help investors understand the return of an investment compared to its risk. The ratio is the average return earned over the risk-free rate per unit of volatility or total risk. For example, a Sharpe ratio of 0.5 indicates that the investmentโs return is generating 0.5 units of excess return for each unit of risk taken, relative to the risk-free rate. If Sharpe ratio is greater than 1.0, then it is considered to be an acceptable portfolio for investors. A ratio higher than 2.0 is rated as very good. A ratio of 3.0 or higher is considered an excellent portfolio. A ratio under 1.0 is considered sub-optimal.


        `


