        One way to use the Price to Earnings (P/E) ratio in the search for good stocks is to identify companies with a low P/E ratio compared to other companies in the same industry. The P/E ratio is considered a multiple, meaning it tells investors how much they are willing to pay for each unit (e.g., riyal or dollar) of the companyโs earnings. This ratio can be used to compare two or more companies. The most common use of the P/E ratio is to assess the valuation of a stock or index. The higher the ratio, the more expensive the stock is relative to its earnings; the lower the ratio, the less expensive it is.
Companies with high P/E ratios are often considered growth stocks. This indicates positive future performance, as investors have high expectations for future earnings growth and are willing to buy the stock. The downside is that growth stocks often have higher volatility, which puts pressure on the companies to perform well enough to justify their higher valuations. For this reason, investing in growth stocks is considered a risky investment.
Stocks with high P/E ratios can also be considered overvalued. On the other hand, companies with low P/E ratios are often considered undervalued, as their stock prices trade below their intrinsic value. This mispricing is seen as a good deal and encourages investors to buy the stock before the market corrects its price. When that happens, investors profit from the stock price increase. Examples of low P/E stocks can often be found in mature industries that pay a steady rate of dividends.


Letโs assume that Stock (A) is trading at 30 SAR and Stock (B) at 20 SAR. This does not necessarily mean that Stock (A) is more expensive.
The price-to-earnings (P/E) ratio can help us determine which of the two stocks is cheaper from a valuation perspective. If the average P/E ratio in the sector is 15, and Stock (A) has a P/E of 15 while Stock (B) has a P/E of 30, then Stock (A) is considered cheaper even though its absolute price is higher than Stock (B), because there is less being paid per riyal of current earnings.
However, the fact that Stock (B) has a higher P/E than both its competitors and the sector average may suggest that investors expect higher future earnings growth compared to the market.
Itโs important to compare a companyโs P/E ratio with its peers in the same sector. However, here are some general guidelines that help in evaluating the P/E ratio:
P/E ratio below 10: The company may be undervalued or facing challenges (such as slow growth or specific risks).
P/E ratio from 10 to 20: Considered acceptable for stable or mature companies.
P/E ratio from 20 to 30: Indicates good growth and strong earnings expectations.
P/E ratio above 30: Suggests high growth expectations or possibly an overvalued stock.


